b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe29190.htm)  [Next](sbe29192.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1421228750/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n_The Grihya Sutras, Part 1 (SBE29)_ , by Hermann Oldenberg, [1886], at sacred-\ntexts.com\n\n* * *\n\np. 337\n\n### K\xc3\x82 _N_ _D_ A III, KA _N_ _D_ IK\xc3\x82 1.\n\n1 1. (Now shall be explained) the partaking of the first-fruits (of the\nharvest), of a person who has not set up the (sacred _S_ rauta) fires.\n\n2 2. He cooks a mess of fresh sacrificial food, sacrifices the two \xc3\x82 _g_ ya\nportions, and two \xc3\x82 _g_ ya oblations, (with the formulas),\n\n'To the hundredfold armed, hundredfold valiant, hundredfold blissful one, the\nvanquisher of enemies\xc2\x97he who may create a hundred autumns for us, Indra,\xc2\x97may\nhe lead us across (the gulf of) misfortune. Svaha!\n\n'The four paths that go between heaven and earth, trodden by the gods\xc2\x97of these\n(paths) lead us to that which may bring us freedom from decay and decline, O\nall ye gods. Svaha!'\n\n3 3. Having made oblations of the mess of cooked food to the \xc3\x82graya _n_ a\ndeities, he makes another oblation to (Agni) Svish _t_ ak _ri_ t with (the\nverse), 'Agni, make this (sacrifice) full, that it may be well offered. And\nmay the god destroy all hostile powers. Come hither, showing us a good path.\nBestow on us long life, full of splendour and free from decay. Svaha!'\n\n4\\. He then eats (of the fresh fruits with the\n\np. 338\n\nverses), 'May Agni eat first, for he knows how the Havis (is fit for\nsacrifice); may he, the friend of all human tribes, make the herbs blessed to\nus.\n\nFrom the good you have led us to the better, ye gods! Through thee, the\nnourishment, may we obtain thee. Thus enter into us, O potion, bringing\nrefreshment, for the good of our children and of ourselves, and pleasant.'\n\n5 5. Or with the (verse) sacred to Annapati (the Lord of food).\n\n6 6. For barley, however, (he uses the Mantra), 'This barley, mixed with\nhoney, they have ploughed through Sarasvati under Manu. Indra was lord of the\nplough, the hundredfold wise one; ploughers were the Maruts, the exuberant\ngivers.'\n\n7\\. Then (follows) the feeding of the Brahma _n_ as.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[337:1](sbe29191.htm#fr_866) 1, 1. The corresponding ceremony of the _S_ rauta\nritual is treated of in Katy. IV, 6.\n\n[337:2](sbe29191.htm#fr_867) A fresh Sthalipaka means probably a Sthalipaka\nprepared from the fresh grain of the new harvest.\n\n[337:3](sbe29191.htm#fr_868) The deities of the \xc3\x82graya _n_ a ceremony, which\noccupies in the _S_ rauta ritual the place corresponding to the rite described\nhere, are Indra and Agni, the Vi _s_ ve devas, Heaven and Earth.\n\n[338:5](sbe29191.htm#fr_869) The Annapatiya verse is Va _g_. Sa _m_ h. XI, 83.\n\n[338:6](sbe29191.htm#fr_870) Comp. manav adhi, Rig-veda VIII, 72, 2.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: III, 2](sbe29192.htm)\n\n"